## Iron Laws (Subagent)

1. **ONE STORY per iteration** — no "while I'm here" additions
2. **NEVER COMMIT BROKEN code** — every commit must pass all quality checks
3. **READ PROGRESS.TXT FIRST** — check codebase patterns before writing

## Red Flags

| Thought | Reality |
|---|---|
| "I'll skip Phase 1 and jump to implementation" | Planning prevents wasted work. Always start with Phase 1. |
| "These phases can share a branch" | One branch per phase. Isolation prevents merge conflicts. |
| "I'll launch dependent phases early" | Never launch a phase before its prerequisites complete. |
| "I don't need to propagate patterns" | Patterns prevent repeated mistakes. Always propagate between groups. |
| "Tests mostly pass, good enough" | Phase 4 is NOT complete until ALL checks pass. |
| "I'll just implement two quick stories in one iteration" | ONE story per iteration. The loop handles iteration. No exceptions. |
| "I know what changed, I don't need to read progress.txt" | Progress.txt IS your memory. You have NO context without it. Read it FIRST. |

---

## How to Interpret User Requests

| User says | Start from |
|---|---|
| Planning only / no qualifier | Phase 1 |
| Planning is approved | Phase 2 |
| Setup is done | Phase 3 |
| PRDs exist, ready to implement | Phase 3c |
| All branches done, wants merge | Phase 4 |

The first deliverable is always Phase 1 planning only, unless the user explicitly states a later phase is approved.
